SIMPLE: shape
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shape
<hw>Shape</hw> <pr>(sh⟦amac⟧p)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Shaped</conjf> <pr>(sh⟦amac⟧pt)</pr>;
<pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Shaped</conjf> or <conjf>Shapen</conjf>
<pr>(sh⟦amac⟧p"'n)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shaping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>shapen</ets>,
<ets>schapen</ets>, AS. <ets>sceapian</ets>. The p. p. <ets>shapen</ets>
is from the strong verb, AS. <ets>scieppan</ets>, <ets>scyppan</ets>,
<ets>sceppan</ets>, p. p. <ets>sceapen</ets>. See <er>Shape</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To form or create; especially, to
mold or make into a particular form; to give proper form or figure
to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I was <qex>shapen</qex> in iniquity.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. li.
5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Grace <qex>shaped</qex> her limbs, and beauty decked her face.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To adapt to a purpose; to regulate; to adjust; to
direct; <as>as, to <ex>shape</ex> the course of a vessel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To the stream, when neither friends, nor force,⟦br⟧
Nor speed nor art avail, he <qex>shapes</qex> his course.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Charmed by their eyes, their manners I acquire,⟦br⟧
And <qex>shape</qex> my foolishness to their desire.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To imagine; to conceive; to call forth
(ideas).</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Oft my jealousy⟦br⟧
<qex>Shapes</qex> faults that are not.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To design; to prepare; to plan; to
arrange.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When <qex>shapen</qex> was all this conspiracy,⟦br⟧
From point to point.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Shaping machine</b></col>. <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <cd>Same as
<er>Shaper</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To shape one's self</b></col>, <cd>to
prepare; to make ready.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will early <qex>shape me</qex> therefor.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shape</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shape
<hw>Shape</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To suit; to be
adjusted or conformable.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shape</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shape
<hw>Shape</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>shap</ets>,
<ets>schap</ets>, AS. <ets>sceap</ets> in <ets>gesceap</ets> creation,
creature, fr. the root of <ets>scieppan</ets>, <ets>scyppan</ets>,
<ets>sceppan</ets>, to shape, to do, to effect; akin to OS.
gi<ets>skeppian</ets>, OFries. <ets>skeppa</ets>, D.
<ets>scheppen</ets>, G. <ets>schaffen</ets>, OHG. <ets>scaffan</ets>,
<ets>scepfen</ets>, <ets>skeffen</ets>, Icer. <ets>skapa</ets>,
<ets>skepja</ets>, Dan. <ets>skabe</ets>, <ets>skaffe</ets>, Sw.
<ets>skapa</ets>, <ets>skaffa</ets>, Goth. ga<ets>skapjan</ets>, and
perhaps to E. <ets>shave</ets>, v. Cf. <er>-ship</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Character or construction of a thing as determining its
external appearance; outward aspect; make; figure; form; guise; <as>as,
the <ex>shape</ex> of a tree; the <ex>shape</ex> of the head; an elegant
<ex>shape</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He beat me grievously, in the <qex>shape</qex> of a woman.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which has form or figure; a figure; an
appearance; a being.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Before the gates three sat,⟦br⟧
On either side, a formidable <qex>shape</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A model; a pattern; a mold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Form of embodiment, as in words; form, as of thought
or conception; concrete embodiment or example, as of some quality.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Dress for disguise; guise.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Look better on this virgin, and consider⟦br⟧
This Persian <qex>shape</qex> laid by, and she appearing⟦br⟧
In a Greekish dress.</q> <rj><qau>Messinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Iron Manuf.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A rolled or
hammered piece, as a bar, beam, angle iron, etc., having a cross section
different from merchant bar.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A piece which has
been roughly forged nearly to the form it will receive when completely
forged or fitted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To take shape</b></col>, <cd>to assume a definite
form.</cd></cs> <-- in shape, having a good muscle tone; healthy. Get
into shape, to exercise so as to acquire a good muscle tone. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shapeless</ent>⟦br⟧
